In case you haven't seen this (I hadn't until now), we might be able to get an early look at cases here: https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-response-reporting "Updated Monday-Friday by 5 p.m." This page gives the number of confirmed cases for Oct 14 as 1,512 and the number of probable cases as 137, which sums to 1649, the same as the nytimes number for new cases on Oct 14 shown here: https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/massachusetts-covid-cases.html So you can get earlier case numbers from the nytimes web page, not scaled per 100k like our resolution data, but I think we can figure that out. Also note that the resolution data says "confirmed cases," so it may exclude probable cases. Confirmed + probable: Oct 13: 1763 Oct 14: 1789 Oct 15: 1649 Average: 1734 The mass.gov page only goes through Oct 14, so it will likely only give data through Oct 17 by 5pm today, but at least that would give us something. @JonathanMann @paulm @Ryan-Beck @Emking @meterplech @oracle100

Going up a bit on the first bucket. The number to beat from September 7th is 23.4. Currently at 20.2. I'm guessing we'll see a number in the 50s for today which would mean the number for tomorrow just has to be below around 30 to keep the average below 23.4. That seems very doable, there hasn't been a non-monday/holiday weekly number above 30 since September 17th when case counts were higher. Could be wrong about today being in the 50s though, we'll see what happens!

The avg over the last 4 days is 24.4 (which is above Sept 7) and with the risk of a correction spike, plus dropping that data from the 11th, I think there's a much higher chance of this falling into Bin 1 than is being accounted for at this point.

Well, this is the question that just keeps giving (a headache mainly). Summing up, I think there is consensus that bin2 is out, for four good reasons; 1 As stipulated in the first sentence of the question, "The outcome will be determined using data as provided by 91-DIVOC (91-DIVOC, parameters are set with the link)" 2 The dropdown menu below the chart states that the data we are seeing represents "New cases 1-wk average" 3 Alongside the Y axis it says "7-day average" 4 The data is in fact showing a 7-day rolling average (as confirmed by @Emking et al.) Case for defence rests. Prosecution claims that the labelling is not consistent on the pop-up for each day and can be misleading. So it's either bin1 or bin3 for me.

Ok, I was at 100% on bin 3 for quite a while on this question. Have I learned my lesson about that yet? Apparently not. We know 3 values that will count for this question so far: 28, 25.7, 23.7. The trend in those numbers may be downward, but if MA is overall heading upward or flat, this could easily resolve to bin 1. Thanks to @JonathanMann for the nudge.
My gut is almost 50/50, or as close to @JonathanMann's forecast here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1344807

This could really go either way, but, if the true underlying case counts average 22 per day or more from now to the question expiration, this will resolve as bin 1. Nulls make the data tricky to parse, but look at today's count in the daily numbers. I had originally anticipated a ramp up culminating in a "data bomb" spike on the 18th, but, due to nulls, there will be no ramp up. Counts will remain exactly as they are today for the next two iterations and then suddenly *bam* "data bomb" spike for the 18th (appearing the morning of the 19th, unless there is a serious decline in real underlying cases). The 19th (appearing the 20th) will be lower than the 18th, but could still end up at a place where bin 1 resolves as true when the question resolves (slight edge for bin 1 over bin 3 as per my forecast).

The lack of reporting on Columbus day made the 7-day average for Oct 11th consist of only four data points rather than five. Thus, because the lack of weekend reporting is counted as zero rather than null, bin 2 has been eliminated. There will be a spike next Monday, pushing the average up to 26 cases per day (as that day will include an extra day in the calculation). But, the value should drop back under 21 on October 19th as the data catches up.

Assumptions: * No new variant that replaces Delta in the next 6 weeks. * The majority of schools have started in late August or before Labor Day. Therefore most changes resulting from back to school (such as more testing or more cases) have already been seen, but we'll see some small additional increases. * Vaccinations will continue to increase at a low rate, won't have a significant impact. Booster shots might start in late September, but since it takes about 7 days to have an impact, they will also have a minimal impact at reducing cases. * The weather won't be too cold until mid October, so no increases due to winter. * The number of cases reported depends on the number of cases and the number of tests. * The real number of cases has likely peaked. It is likely to start going down. I don't yet have high confidence on this. * The number of tests might go up a bit due to school starts, and then probably stay flat or go down as cases stabilize / go down. * There are no holidays that will have an artificial impact (less testing) * Therefore: - Bin 1 is very unlikely - Bin 2 is not too likely, but might happen if the numbers haven't yet peaked. Need to track over the next few days. - Bin 3 is unlikely. - Bin 4 is the most likely

It looks as if cases have peaked, but I'm not quite convinced yet. MA has a relatively high proportion of fully vaccinated people (>67% overall), and the younger age groups (12-29yrs) average 68-71% for the first dose. However, Hampden and Bristol counties, which have some of the higher levels of cases, also have the lowest levels of vaccination, which suggests there is still scope for further transmission. Daily testing rates and positivity levels are fairly flat, but with schools and higher education open I think there could be slightly more testing over the next weeks, which could lead to flat or marginally increasing cases being recorded, before a decline starts to trend. So bin1 is almost ruled out; if case av. falls that low, it's unlikely to be reversed over the term Bin2: I can't rule this out; Delta could still spread through younger groups, and the control week included a day with almost no cases recorded Bin3: I think it would take a few weeks to hit 28.5 and that would signal that transmission is persisting, so this looks unlikely Bin4: this looks the most likely with rising vaccination rates in younger ages, mask mandates, a plateauing chart. I'll go for a gradual rise for a few weeks, followed by a decline into October.
I may be going too far out on a limb here, but with how vaccinated MA is and that their Delta wave does seem to have peaked, I see a broad, slow, perhaps wavy decline through the forecast period.

23.4 per 100k on Sep 7, 2021. And it looks to me like MA is near a peak of the Delta wave. I anticipate a slower decline of the Delta wave than its rise, because of spread in schools, seasonality starting to kick in, and some waning immunity; I think it's possible we could even see a second, lower peak at some point this fall. But I expect that overall, cases will be lower in the forecast period than they are now (with the small possibility of a slightly higher peak soon). I 100% think that the answer will be bin 4, but I also 100% know it's best to hedge one's bets, at least a little.
